1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Most AI assistants start every session from zero.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:16,000
DREAM gives Qwen Cloud durable experience, then governs conflicts, forgetting, context budgets, provenance, and feedback.

3
00:00:16,000 --> 00:00:26,000
In Session 1, Qwen recognizes a durable rollout preference and returns remember.

4
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:38,000
In Session 2, Qwen returns supersede, and DREAM marks the old value inactive instead of keeping two conflicting truths.

5
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Session 3 starts with no prompt history and a hard 64-token context budget.

6
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:59,000
DREAM recalls only the current 20 percent canary for 45 minutes. The old value does not leak.

7
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:06,000
Helpful and correct feedback is written back to future ranking.

8
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:17,000
We ran 37 real Qwen curator decisions across 24 synthetic lifecycle cases.

9
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:28,000
Cases cover preference carryover, conflict supersession, TTL, explicit forgetting, duplicates, and limited context.

10
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:40,000
All 24 cases passed. Critical recall was 100 percent, forbidden leak was zero, and budget compliance was 100 percent.

11
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:48,000
Organizational claims must retain source proof and human approval.

12
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:56,000
Unresolved conflicts are blocked from retrieval.

13
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:08,000
Approved current truth enters the Requirement Case, impact map, engineering brief, and Jira draft with provenance.

14
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:17,000
DREAM runs on Alibaba Cloud Function Compute with qwen3.7-plus.

15
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:29,000
The benchmark, full report, tests, runtime proof, and deployment template are public in the repository.

16
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:40,000
DREAM helps Qwen remember the right experience, replace old truth, forget safely, and explain what it used.
